      "label": "Transcript",
      "value": "Hyde Park, Jan 7th [74?]\nDear Cousin Marianna,\n\nMother has\nfound herself too feeble since\nAuntie's death to answer\nthe many letters that have\npoured in upon her firm\nkind and sympathizing\nfriends altho they have been\nof the greatest comfort to\nher, so she has asked me\nto relieve her of this task which\nis a delightful one to me.\nYou know how many, many\nfriends Aunty had. I find\nit is no light duty to tell\neach one all they want to\nknow. I wish I might tell\nyou of last words and fare-\nwell messages of my dear Aunt\n\n[End page 1]\n\nbut she never spoke of her\napproaching end though she\nremained in the article of death\nas much as three whole days\nand retained her faculties\nto the last. It was sad for\nus to see her thus pass from\nus, but we feel that she was\nfully conscious of her situation\nbut wished to spare us all the\npain of parting. Especially\nwas she tender of my brother,\nwho could not bring himself\nto giver her up and who be-\nlieved to the last that she\nwould be returned again to\nhim. Her death is a great\naffliction to him. He has been\nher constant companion and\nnurse these past few months\nlifting her in his arms\nand tending her like a baby.\n\n[End page 2]\n\nTruly the light of his life\nseems to have gone out, Pray\ndear Cousin that this earthly\nprop being taken from him\nhe may turn his heart\nto the Savior for consolation.\nWe never turn to our Heavenly\nFather till all earthly help is\ngone.\n\nOf Auntie's last days there\nis little to be said. She caught\na violent cold ten days before\nher death, which settled on her\nlungs causing toward the last\ngreat difficulty of breathing.\n\nMother could not be induced\nto leave her bedside for a mo-\nment, and sympathizing so\ndeftly in her sufferings she\nfound herself very weak after\nAunties death. She is now\nmeasurably recovered\n\n[End page 3]\n\nTho. she said nothing of her\napproaching death, to father\nmother or Stuart, she wrote\na precious [note?] to my husband\nfour days before which has been\nof great comfort to us, for it\nshowed that after so many\nyears of [skepticism?] her heart\nwas turning [now?] more to\nChrist as her Savior.\n\nShe received\nthe letter you speak of in [illegible]\nto hers of Nov 14th and enjoyed\nit much. You speak of her great\nunselfishness. A dear Espiscopal\nfriend of hers said to me after\nher death. Your Aunts mind\nhad wandered for many years\nfrom the Lord, but her good\nworks kept her very near the\nhear of Christ. She told me\nlast summer that for the past\n\n[End page 4]\n\ntwo years Christ had been\nnearer to her than for many\nyears before. The remem-\nbrance of the early days of her\nconversion kept coming up\nto her.\n\nI was very much pleased\nat Darsy's remembrance of me.\nTell her it his in my bible.\nI had a letter from Llewelyn's\nwife tho the day in which\nshe speaks with deep interest\nof her sisters, whose visit she\nenjoyed so much last sum-\nmer. I hope in the coming\nyears I shall be able to see\nmore of them. I have been\nvery much drawn to Edward\nsince hearing of his conversion,\nand hope he may be a [mean?]\n\n[End page 5]\n\nof bringing his brother to the\nlight! Both Llewellyn and\nEmma are very much attach-\ned to him.\n\nMother enclosed\nthis sad letter from Elizabeth\nBrown in hopes that you can\nhelp her. We have sent them\nall of Auntie's clothes [two trunks\nfull] as it was her wish and\nthis will enable the women\nto get through the winter comfort-\nably as far as clothes are con-\ncerned, but they seem to her\nin need of much more. Hoping\nyou can assist them at this\ntrying time.\n\nI remain,\nAffectionately your cousin\nSarah Hamilton\n\nI am so glad I have been able\nto find a lock of Auntie's hair\nfor you.\n\n[End page 6]"
